Important Edge Cases Interviewers Ask
Can we have a constructor in an abstract class?
Yes. Abstract classes can have constructors, called via super() from child class.
Can a constructor be private?
Yes — this is used in the Singleton pattern to prevent outside instantiation.
javaclass Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() {}   // private constructor

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null)
            instance = new Singleton();
        return instance;
    }
}
What if you define a parameterized constructor but no default?
Java does NOT auto-generate the default constructor anymore — calling new Car() will fail.
javaclass Car {
    Car(String brand) {}   // only parameterized
}
Car c = new Car();   // ❌ compile error — no default constructor

One-line Interview Answer

"A constructor is a special block that initializes an object when it's created. It has the same name as the class and no return type. It cannot explicitly return a value, but implicitly the JVM returns the newly created object's reference after construction.
